Another example

Suppose you want the square root.

#include <math.h>

int main()
{
    printf("%f", sqrt(25));

    return 0;
}

Here,

sqrt()

is declared in

math.h
What happens if you don't include the header?
int main()
{
    printf("Hello");
}

Modern compilers will usually report an error or warning such as:

implicit declaration of function 'printf'

because the compiler hasn't seen the declaration of printf().


/**  Angle brackets (<>) vs Double quotes ("") **/

There are two ways to include a header.

// System header//

#include <stdio.h>

The compiler searches the standard include directories.
Use this for standard library headers.

// User-defined header //

Suppose you create
mymath.h

Then include it like this:
#include "mymath.h"

The compiler searches your project directory first.

Example of your own header file

Suppose you create

add.h
int add(int, int);

Now

main.c
#include <stdio.h>
#include "add.h"

int main()
{
    printf("%d", add(5, 6));
}

And

add.c
int add(int a, int b)
{
    return a + b;
}

This is how large C projects are organized.

Header File vs Source File
Header File (.h)	                        Source File (.c)
Contains declarations	                Contains implementations
Included using #include	                Compiled into object code
Usually stores function prototypes	    Stores actual function definitions
Shared among multiple source files	    Contains executable code

